<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-05-10T22:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-05-10T22:00:00-05:00" n="121" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d121">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/13079: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-05-11T11:00:00+08:00">May 11, 1935—11
                                a.m.</date><lb/>[Received May 11—2:45 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>192. Reference Legation’s 186, May 7, 10 a.m.<note n="42" xml:id="d121fn42">Not printed.</note> Ringwalt<note n="43" xml:id="d121fn43">Arthur R. Ringwalt, Vice Consul at
                                Yunnanfu.</note> reports that Chiang Kai-shek arrived at Yunnanfu on
                            May 10th. He also reports that several thousand Reds are believed to be
                            still in the mountains north of Wuting and that the majority have
                            crossed the Yangtze River at various places above and below Tungan.</p>
                        <closer>For the Minister:<lb/><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Lockhart</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>